00:26:57.430 --> 00:26:58.890 align:middle line:90%
for each of those things.

00:26:58.890 --> 00:27:01.120 align:middle line:84%
But these things expanded
the realm of my consciousness

00:27:01.120 --> 00:27:03.170 align:middle line:84%
and I know there is
a truth and a reality

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:05.510 align:middle line:84%
there that I can
bring back to science.

00:27:05.510 --> 00:27:10.210 align:middle line:84%
So I have to choose which
things to be outrageous about.

00:27:10.210 --> 00:27:12.970 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's-- I mean
that's very, very sobering.

00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:17.110 align:middle line:84%
Because of course,
to my knowledge,

00:27:17.110 --> 00:27:19.740 align:middle line:84%
you don't have, like,
a job at a university

00:27:19.740 --> 00:27:22.870 align:middle line:84%
that could be threatened by,
you know, something, like this.

00:27:22.870 --> 00:27:24.700 align:middle line:84%
Right, and if I had
a job at a university,

00:27:24.700 --> 00:27:26.200 align:middle line:90%
I would be far more constrained.

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:28.610 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I'm
so incredibly lucky

00:27:28.610 --> 00:27:32.470 align:middle line:84%
that I don't have a conventional
scientific position.

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:33.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's--

00:27:33.510 --> 00:27:35.550 align:middle line:84%
But then considering
all of that,

00:27:35.550 --> 00:27:38.190 align:middle line:84%
why take such a negative stance
as what you did in your earlier

00:27:38.190 --> 00:27:40.090 align:middle line:84%
episode where you're kind of
like-- when I brought it up,

00:27:40.090 --> 00:27:42.000 align:middle line:84%
you were kind of, like, pushing
it away with such force,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.340 align:middle line:84%
which is so much the
condescending attitude that you

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:46.030 align:middle line:84%
get from most people who
are in the scientific

00:27:46.030 --> 00:27:49.250 align:middle line:84%
world view about psychic
experience or paranormal--

00:27:49.250 --> 00:27:50.610 align:middle line:84%
Because of all the
years-- remember,

00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:52.900 align:middle line:84%
this was extremely
popular when I was a kid.

00:27:52.900 --> 00:27:55.080 align:middle line:84%
And I did get into science
at the age of 10, which

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:57.560 align:middle line:90%
means that I got in in 1953.

00:27:57.560 --> 00:28:00.370 align:middle line:84%
And that means that in
the first six or seven

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:02.440 align:middle line:84%
years of my
immersion in science,

00:28:02.440 --> 00:28:04.710 align:middle line:90%
this was a very strong current.

00:28:04.710 --> 00:28:08.070 align:middle line:84%
I never found
anything useful in it.

00:28:08.070 --> 00:28:10.490 align:middle line:84%
Did I find anything
useful in peyote?

00:28:10.490 --> 00:28:14.360 align:middle line:84%
Immediately-- immediately,
the doors of perception

00:28:14.360 --> 00:28:16.710 align:middle line:84%
started opening, to use
Aldous Huxley's phrase.

00:28:16.710 --> 00:28:19.650 align:middle line:84%
But-- but-- but useful is
different than true, no?

00:28:19.650 --> 00:28:22.330 align:middle line:84%
I never found anything
that rang true in it.

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:26.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, one day when I was 18
and had dropped out of school

00:28:26.450 --> 00:28:28.490 align:middle line:84%
and was seeking Satori
Zen Buddhist enlightenment

00:28:28.490 --> 00:28:30.260 align:middle line:84%
and people were dropping
out of their jobs

00:28:30.260 --> 00:28:34.180 align:middle line:84%
and following me, I was alone in
a great big coal car on the way

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:37.460 align:middle line:84%
from God knows
what-- what railroad

00:28:37.460 --> 00:28:41.530 align:middle line:84%
town in-- in
California to Nevada--

00:28:41.530 --> 00:28:43.980 align:middle line:90%
a long trip and a painful one.

00:28:43.980 --> 00:28:45.070 align:middle line:90%
And coal cars have a--

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:46.700 align:middle line:84%
Maybe-- maybe you're
next to be the next--

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:47.800 align:middle line:84%
you're meant to
be the next world

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:50.670 align:middle line:84%
avatar or kalki but you've got
kind of distracted by science.

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:51.820 align:middle line:90%
Well, here's what happened.

00:28:51.820 --> 00:28:56.120 align:middle line:84%
The coal cars and
freight cars in general

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:59.210 align:middle line:84%
do not have any
suspension system.

00:28:59.210 --> 00:29:01.090 align:middle line:90%
So you cannot sit.

00:29:01.090 --> 00:29:03.470 align:middle line:84%
You have to stand or you
would bounce like this.

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:06.120 align:middle line:84%
Your ass would hit that
metal over and over again.

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:08.090 align:middle line:90%
It would be horribly disruptive.

00:29:08.090 --> 00:29:09.420 align:middle line:90%
So you stand the whole way.

00:29:09.420 --> 00:29:11.200 align:middle line:84%
Because it's a coal
car, there's coal.

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:13.410 align:middle line:84%
It's sweeping from
the rear of the car up

00:29:13.410 --> 00:29:15.280 align:middle line:84%
to the front
convection currents,

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:18.240 align:middle line:84%
then going up
above the car's rim

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:20.020 align:middle line:84%
and coming back at
65 miles an hour.

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:21.870 align:middle line:84%
Your followers must have
been kind of pissed at you.

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:23.800 align:middle line:84%
Well, so you're--
you're being-- your face

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:26.090 align:middle line:90%
is being sand blasted by coal.

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:29.230 align:middle line:84%
And when-- when
the coal car stops,

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:30.680 align:middle line:84%
the way they get the
coal out of the car

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:34.190 align:middle line:84%
is that the entire floor is
six huge flaps with levers.

00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:36.790 align:middle line:84%
The lever holds
the flap in place.

00:29:36.790 --> 00:29:38.770 align:middle line:84%
At a certain point
after three hours

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:44.240 align:middle line:84%
standing in this coal car being
sandblasted, I had a feeling.

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:46.240 align:middle line:84%
And I decided to
move my knapsack

00:29:46.240 --> 00:29:52.510 align:middle line:84%
and myself from the left front
flap to the right front flap.

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:56.590 align:middle line:84%
10 minutes later, there
was an enormous clang.

00:29:56.590 --> 00:29:59.990 align:middle line:84%
And that flap I had been
standing up for 3 and 1/2 hours

00:29:59.990 --> 00:30:01.500 align:middle line:90%
flapped open.

00:30:01.500 --> 00:30:05.230 align:middle line:84%
If I'd still been standing
there, I'd be a hamburger

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:06.460 align:middle line:84%
or I would have
been a hamburger.

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:07.910 align:middle line:84%
I would have disappeared
a long time ago.

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:09.690 align:middle line:90%
I wouldn't be here with you.

00:30:09.690 --> 00:30:11.570 align:middle line:90%
Is that a paranormal experience?

00:30:11.570 --> 00:30:14.500 align:middle line:90%
I've had a number of them.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:15.830 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:30:15.830 --> 00:30:17.790 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't have
that ring of truth.

00:30:17.790 --> 00:30:20.360 align:middle line:84%
It gives me the feeling that it
will provide a tool with which

00:30:20.360 --> 00:30:24.280 align:middle line:90%
I can understand things.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:27.380 align:middle line:90%
And peyote did.

00:30:27.380 --> 00:30:31.870 align:middle line:84%
And LSD did, even though
I only did them twice.

00:30:31.870 --> 00:30:33.850 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes, you
feel that something

00:30:33.850 --> 00:30:35.990 align:middle line:84%
is going to be something
that you can use

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:40.230 align:middle line:84%
to pry a reality out of
the wall of a coal mine

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:43.270 align:middle line:84%
and turn into an
object of amazement.

00:30:43.270 --> 00:30:45.190 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes, they
don't impress you

00:30:45.190 --> 00:30:46.760 align:middle line:90%
as being those kinds of tools.

00:30:46.760 --> 00:30:51.610 align:middle line:84%
And you have to pass on the
ones that don't feel like tools.

00:30:51.610 --> 00:30:57.920 align:middle line:84%
Well, I would say if any
instincts or intuition

00:30:57.920 --> 00:31:01.570 align:middle line:84%
or whatever you want to call
it would be considered useful,

00:31:01.570 --> 00:31:04.950 align:middle line:90%
that would be one of them.

00:31:04.950 --> 00:31:10.080 align:middle line:84%
I-- I-- you know, it doesn't
get more useful than that.

00:31:10.080 --> 00:31:12.740 align:middle line:90%
But we don't know that.

00:31:12.740 --> 00:31:17.660 align:middle line:84%
You know, another thing I think
that-- that is worth mentioning

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:25.840 align:middle line:84%
is for the sake of analysis,
we divide the senses

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:27.940 align:middle line:90%
into these various categories.

00:31:27.940 --> 00:31:29.710 align:middle line:90%
This is, you know, sensory.

00:31:29.710 --> 00:31:32.750 align:middle line:90%
This is olfactory, so on, so on.

00:31:32.750 --> 00:31:36.650 align:middle line:84%
They're obviously not
very well distinguished.

00:31:36.650 --> 00:31:38.750 align:middle line:84%
You know, the sense of
taste and sense of smell

00:31:38.750 --> 00:31:42.800 align:middle line:90%
are inexplicably linked, yeah.

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:45.290 align:middle line:84%
And I have to say
that what a lot of we

00:31:45.290 --> 00:31:48.890 align:middle line:84%
think of with intuition, kind
of gut feeling, you know,

00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:53.640 align:middle line:84%
is-- is not necessarily all
that radically different

00:31:53.640 --> 00:31:54.970 align:middle line:90%
from the other senses.

00:31:54.970 --> 00:31:57.990 align:middle line:84%
It's just one that we, you
know, for various reasons,

00:31:57.990 --> 00:32:01.000 align:middle line:84%
have-- have chosen not to
pay attention to or develop.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:05.760 align:middle line:84%
So there-- there's-- to
what extent you're feeling

00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:07.070 align:middle line:84%
someone's eyes on
the back of your head

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:10.480 align:middle line:84%
is some kind of extension
of peripheral vision.

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:11.610 align:middle line:90%
Maybe you did catch a glance.

00:32:11.610 --> 00:32:13.830 align:middle line:84%
I think there are two-- I
think there are at least two--

00:32:13.830 --> 00:32:16.340 align:middle line:84%
Do you know that book that
[INAUDIBLE] did about man's

00:32:16.340 --> 00:32:19.150 align:middle line:84%
possible future evolution
where he talked about how

00:32:19.150 --> 00:32:20.840 align:middle line:84%
our intuitive
faculties, our cognitive

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:23.520 align:middle line:84%
faculties that just are
so much faster than our--

00:32:23.520 --> 00:32:24.880 align:middle line:84%
than our rational
faculties, they're

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:27.150 align:middle line:84%
like in another
category altogether.

00:32:27.150 --> 00:32:29.370 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I think
they're sufficiently

00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:31.970 align:middle line:90%
different to make a difference.

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:34.380 align:middle line:84%
I want to wrap up soon, but
go ahead and make your comment.

00:32:34.380 --> 00:32:37.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, one day-- OK, one
day, my friend Val Geiss

00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:39.160 align:middle line:84%
who's a leading
expert on large animal

00:32:39.160 --> 00:32:41.300 align:middle line:84%
be-- one of the leading
experts on large animal

00:32:41.300 --> 00:32:43.810 align:middle line:84%
behavior in the world was
doing what Val Geiss does.

00:32:43.810 --> 00:32:46.360 align:middle line:84%
Six months of the year, he puts
on a knapsack, gets a rifle,

00:32:46.360 --> 00:32:49.280 align:middle line:84%
and goes up into the mountains
and follows the mountain

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:53.070 align:middle line:84%
sheep and lives like a mountain
sheep and lives off the land.

00:32:53.070 --> 00:32:56.570 align:middle line:84%
Every once in a while, Val
would encounter a grizzly bear.

00:32:56.570 --> 00:32:58.890 align:middle line:84%
And Val loves it when he
encounters grizzly bears.

00:32:58.890 --> 00:33:01.610 align:middle line:84%
Because this is a
status hierarchy match.

00:33:01.610 --> 00:33:03.940 align:middle line:84%
It's to see who's the
biggest guy on the block.

00:33:03.940 --> 00:33:06.090 align:middle line:84%
And the grizzly bear
stands up on his hind legs

00:33:06.090 --> 00:33:07.530 align:middle line:84%
and makes a great
big show and says,

00:33:07.530 --> 00:33:09.200 align:middle line:84%
I'm the biggest
guy on the block.

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:10.870 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going to terrify you.

00:33:10.870 --> 00:33:13.140 align:middle line:84%
And Val gets up on his
hind legs and says,

00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:14.740 align:middle line:84%
I'm the biggest
guy on the block.

00:33:14.740 --> 00:33:16.420 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to terrify you.

00:33:16.420 --> 00:33:17.470 align:middle line:90%
And it's a showdown.

00:33:17.470 --> 00:33:20.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, one day, it wasn't
a male grizzly bear

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:22.460 align:middle line:90%
Val ran against-- up against.

00:33:22.460 --> 00:33:24.990 align:middle line:84%
He ran across a
female grizzly bear.

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:27.000 align:middle line:84%
And he'd come too
close to her cubs.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.400 align:middle line:90%
And she's not in this for show.

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:31.370 align:middle line:84%
She's in this to
protect her cubs.

00:33:31.370 --> 00:33:34.800 align:middle line:84%
So she took after
Val like a mad woman.

00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:39.750 align:middle line:84%
And all of a sudden, Val had
an out of body experience.

00:33:39.750 --> 00:33:43.030 align:middle line:84%
And it felt to him as if his
consciousness was perching

00:33:43.030 --> 00:33:45.570 align:middle line:84%
on a tree watching
as he saw his body

00:33:45.570 --> 00:33:48.140 align:middle line:84%
scampering across the
landscape looking for a tree

00:33:48.140 --> 00:33:51.990 align:middle line:84%
he could climb and then climbing
that tree until he got high

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:54.190 align:middle line:84%
enough that he could go
out on a branch confident

00:33:54.190 --> 00:33:56.980 align:middle line:84%
that he was high above
the grizzly bears head

00:33:56.980 --> 00:34:01.580 align:middle line:84%
and do a victory dance over her
head hanging from the branch.

00:34:01.580 --> 00:34:05.480 align:middle line:84%
OK, now, Val and I are
materialist scientists, right?

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:08.199 align:middle line:84%
So what do we think about
out of body experiences?

00:34:08.199 --> 00:34:09.929 align:middle line:84%
We have to come up
with a materialist

00:34:09.929 --> 00:34:12.389 align:middle line:90%
or a biological explanation.

00:34:12.389 --> 00:34:14.280 align:middle line:84%
And here's the explanation
we came up with.

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:18.659 align:middle line:84%
And it relates to the difference
between intuition and reason.

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:21.409 align:middle line:84%
In the brain,
normally, things that

00:34:21.409 --> 00:34:23.780 align:middle line:84%
are coming in from
the outdoors--

00:34:23.780 --> 00:34:26.170 align:middle line:84%
you know, sensory
experiences-- they

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:27.580 align:middle line:90%
come up to the limbic system.

00:34:27.580 --> 00:34:32.750 align:middle line:84%
And then they're pursed out to
the cortex to be figured out.

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:35.150 align:middle line:84%
Then, once the cortex
figures them out,

00:34:35.150 --> 00:34:39.370 align:middle line:84%
it sends messages back to move
your arms, move your legs.

00:34:39.370 --> 00:34:42.710 align:middle line:84%
And the gap when the mind
is figuring things out

00:34:42.710 --> 00:34:47.190 align:middle line:84%
is point 0.4 of a second--
4/10 of a second, a little bit

00:34:47.190 --> 00:34:49.280 align:middle line:90%
less than half a second.

00:34:49.280 --> 00:34:51.449 align:middle line:84%
Now, under normal
circumstances, you

00:34:51.449 --> 00:34:54.210 align:middle line:84%
can afford that extra
half a second of time.

00:34:54.210 --> 00:34:58.460 align:middle line:84%
But when the grizzly bear is
really out to end your life

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:02.710 align:middle line:84%
and she's moving as fast as
she possibly can, you cannot

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:05.790 align:middle line:90%
afford that extra half second.

00:35:05.790 --> 00:35:07.560 align:middle line:90%
So what happens?

00:35:07.560 --> 00:35:11.280 align:middle line:84%
The stuff we call intuition,
the nonverbal senses,

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:12.950 align:middle line:90%
take over entirely.

00:35:12.950 --> 00:35:15.380 align:middle line:84%
And they park your
conscious self anywhere

00:35:15.380 --> 00:35:16.900 align:middle line:90%
you want to fantasize being.

00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:17.680 align:middle line:90%
Local tree?

00:35:17.680 --> 00:35:19.200 align:middle line:90%
Fine.

00:35:19.200 --> 00:35:20.370 align:middle line:90%
Cloud in the sky?

00:35:20.370 --> 00:35:22.581 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely fine, just
get out of the way.

00:35:22.581 --> 00:35:23.280 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:26.010 align:middle line:84%
So the incoming stuff can
go up to the limbic system

00:35:26.010 --> 00:35:29.850 align:middle line:84%
and go directly to the outcoming
stuff and not lose your life.

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:33.700 align:middle line:84%
So there are at least two
perceptual systems in there.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:37.640 align:middle line:84%
And they do operate on an
entirely different frame.

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:39.830 align:middle line:84%
Whether they have radically
different perceptions

00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:41.430 align:middle line:84%
of the world or
not, if we weren't

00:35:41.430 --> 00:35:42.800 align:middle line:84%
coming to the end
of the episode,

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:45.170 align:middle line:90%
I could tell you another story.

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:48.720 align:middle line:90%
Let's get Richard's response.

00:35:48.720 --> 00:35:50.660 align:middle line:84%
Well, yeah, the
whole thing about it

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:55.220 align:middle line:84%
is it's all very
well and good to talk

00:35:55.220 --> 00:35:58.290 align:middle line:90%
in terms of brain states.

00:35:58.290 --> 00:36:00.580 align:middle line:84%
But are you really
going to reduce it

00:36:00.580 --> 00:36:02.070 align:middle line:90%
to a question of brain state?

00:36:02.070 --> 00:36:04.710 align:middle line:84%
For example, let's take
something much simpler,

00:36:04.710 --> 00:36:07.810 align:middle line:84%
which is-- well, let's
take something which

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:09.200 align:middle line:84%
is much more complicated
for a minute,

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:12.050 align:middle line:90%
like the experience of God.

00:36:12.050 --> 00:36:15.330 align:middle line:84%
There are people who say, well,
there are some bunch of neurons

00:36:15.330 --> 00:36:17.620 align:middle line:84%
in your brain
that, you know, you

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:21.240 align:middle line:84%
buzz it with an electrode will
produce an experience of God.

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:26.990 align:middle line:84%
Hence, the experience of God is
just something in your brain--

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:30.170 align:middle line:90%
all well and good.

00:36:30.170 --> 00:36:32.780 align:middle line:84%
It's also the case that if
you took the same electrode

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:36.630 align:middle line:84%
and prodded a different
corner of the brain

00:36:36.630 --> 00:36:40.620 align:middle line:84%
that you would have an
experience of light.

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:43.310 align:middle line:84%
We don't conclude from
that that light is

00:36:43.310 --> 00:36:47.930 align:middle line:90%
just a delusion of the brain.

00:36:47.930 --> 00:36:49.300 align:middle line:90%
It may be.

00:36:49.300 --> 00:36:52.880 align:middle line:84%
And I think we would have to
ask that question as seriously

00:36:52.880 --> 00:36:54.730 align:middle line:84%
about physical
experiences like that

00:36:54.730 --> 00:36:57.314 align:middle line:84%
as we would about
religious experiences.

00:36:57.314 --> 00:36:58.880 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, that's--
that's what comes to mind.

00:36:58.880 --> 00:37:00.310 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hm, I like that very much.

00:37:00.310 --> 00:37:01.010 align:middle line:90%
OK, guys.

00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:02.610 align:middle line:84%
For the last question,
I'm going to ask you guys

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:05.350 align:middle line:90%
to reverse your position, OK?

00:37:05.350 --> 00:37:07.520 align:middle line:84%
Howard, can you tell
us-- pretend for a moment

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:09.880 align:middle line:84%
that you've had direct mystical
experiences that totally

00:37:09.880 --> 00:37:11.220 align:middle line:84%
convinced you of
the unitive nature

00:37:11.220 --> 00:37:12.920 align:middle line:84%
of consciousness and
that consciousness

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:14.560 align:middle line:90%
underlies physical reality.

00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:18.060 align:middle line:84%
What would be your
best concise argument

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:20.060 align:middle line:84%
to a scientific
materialist to convince

00:37:20.060 --> 00:37:22.650 align:middle line:90%
them that they're wrong?

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:24.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, I would say,
how in the world

00:37:24.780 --> 00:37:26.430 align:middle line:84%
do you think this
universe got here?

00:37:26.430 --> 00:37:29.210 align:middle line:84%
There's obviously a unity
of some kind that's utterly

00:37:29.210 --> 00:37:31.420 align:middle line:90%
beyond our grasp at the moment.

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:34.260 align:middle line:84%
And if there is, in
fact, a divinity,

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:39.630 align:middle line:84%
the divinity is in every single
quark, every single force,

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:40.570 align:middle line:90%
of this universe.

00:37:40.570 --> 00:37:45.320 align:middle line:84%
And the grand totality then,
absolutely astonishing--

00:37:45.320 --> 00:37:47.920 align:middle line:84%
many totalities layered
with another totalities

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:49.120 align:middle line:90%
of which it consists.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:51.170 align:middle line:84%
And those things are so
far beyond your [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:54.970 align:middle line:10%
as a mere scientist that there
is no way you can even claim

00:37:54.970 --> 00:37:58.590 align:middle line:10%
that your science covers any
more than the small grain

00:37:58.590 --> 00:38:01.750 align:middle line:10%
of reality on a big, big beach.

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:04.740 align:middle line:84%
Nice-- and Richard, pretend
that you're a arch scientific

00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:07.830 align:middle line:84%
materialist having to convince
somebody who has a mystical

00:38:07.830 --> 00:38:09.420 align:middle line:84%
belief system that
there is no such thing

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:10.840 align:middle line:90%
as god or a divine source.

00:38:10.840 --> 00:38:13.000 align:middle line:90%
What would be your argument?

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:16.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, these mystical systems
get very, very convoluted.

00:38:16.420 --> 00:38:18.890 align:middle line:10%
And they are very elaborate.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:21.430 align:middle line:10%
And there are a lot of
different religions saying

00:38:21.430 --> 00:38:23.700 align:middle line:10%
a lot of different things
that are telling us

00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:27.320 align:middle line:10%
that they and they alone
are giving us some sort

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:29.900 align:middle line:10%
of objective view of reality.

00:38:29.900 --> 00:38:32.370 align:middle line:90%
They don't often entirely agree.

00:38:32.370 --> 00:38:35.440 align:middle line:84%
So, you know, I have
to wonder about that.

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:38.710 align:middle line:84%
I have to kind of go also to
kind of an ad hominem argument,

00:38:38.710 --> 00:38:41.230 align:middle line:84%
is like, you know,
what kind of results

00:38:41.230 --> 00:38:43.770 align:middle line:84%
have we gotten from all
of this religious stuff?

00:38:43.770 --> 00:38:47.270 align:middle line:84%
It's often a good excuse for
incredibly brutal behavior.

00:38:47.270 --> 00:38:50.390 align:middle line:84%
That's not-- not really
a logical refutation,

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:53.270 align:middle line:84%
but it does bear
on it, particularly

00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:58.650 align:middle line:84%
since religion is used as
a underpinning for ethics.

00:38:58.650 --> 00:39:01.020 align:middle line:84%
So you have this thing
that underpins ethics

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:02.930 align:middle line:84%
that's-- that's, you
know, seems to be

00:39:02.930 --> 00:39:05.930 align:middle line:84%
used to justify all the worst
